Diagnosis.

Dendrophidion nuchale

is characterized by (
1
) dorsocaudal reduction from 
8
to 
6
occurring posterior to subcaudal 
25
(range, 
27–54
); (
2
) anal plate single or divided (approximately equal frequencies); (
3
) subcaudal counts> 
135 in
males and females; (
4
) ground color of head and body brown; dark crossbands with embedded pale ocelli present on the posterior half or more of the body and tail (

Fig. 
1

); tail not strongly differentiated in color from posterior body; (
5
) blackish or dark brown nuchal collar present in adults (evident or not in juveniles); (
6
) ventral scutes in adults usually with irregular dark anterior borders to each scale (often interrupted midventrally) and sometimes with other irregular dark flecks or spots (

Fig. 
1

); (
8
) total number of enlarged spines on the hemipenis relatively few (<
60
); spines in the distal row uniform in size and numbering <
15
(
12–14
).
